-- Sub-Saharan African Stocks: Housing Finance, KenolKobil, Law Union & Rock
-- Eric Ombok
-- 2010-07-29T16:57:55Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-29/sub-saharan-african-stocks-housing-finance-kenolkobil-law-union-rock.html

          
          
             Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  advanced
for a third day, climbing 0.5 percent to 1,717.25 by the 1:30
p.m. close in Port Louis, the highest in almost six months.  
 Kenya’s  All-Share Index  gained 0.8 percent to close at
76.63 as of 3 p.m. in Nairobi, the highest in more than 22
months. The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index  snapped
seven days of gains, retreating 0.1 percent to 25,905.36 at the
1 p.m. in Lagos, the commercial capital, data from the
exchange’s website show.  
 Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  increased 0.7 percent
to 800.30 at the 4 p.m. close in Windhoek while the  Ghana Stock
Exchange All-Share Index  snapped four days of gains, dropping
0.2 percent to close at 6,373.88 as of 1 p.m. in Accra.  
 The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  
 Housing Finance Co. Ltd.  (HFCL KN), Kenya’s only publicly
traded mortgage company, surged 1.5 shillings, or 6.9 percent,
to 23.25 shillings, the highest level since April 30. The
company plans to expand in East Africa, the Nation newspaper
reported, citing Managing Director  Frank Ireri .  
 KenolKobil Ltd.  (KNOC KN), a Kenyan fuel retailer with
operations in seven African countries, climbed the most in three
weeks, rising 30 cents, or 3.1 percent, to 10.15 shillings.
KenolKobil yesterday reported net income of 1.18 billion
shillings ($14.6 million) in the six months through June,
compared to a loss of 431.2 million shillings in the same period
a year earlier.  
 Law Union & Rock Insurance of Nigeria Plc  (LAWUNION NL)
increased 2 kobo, or 3.9 percent, to 53 kobo. First-quarter
profit increased 17 percent to 124 million naira ($825,840), the
company said in a stock-exchange filing yesterday.  
